1 La concubina di Titone antico 2 già s’imbiancava al balco d’orïente, 3 fuor de le braccia del suo dolce amico;
4 di gemme la sua fronte era lucente, 5 poste in figura del freddo animale 6 che con la coda percuote la gente;
7 e la notte, de’ passi con che sale, 8 fatti avea due nel loco ov’ eravamo, 9 e ’l terzo già chinava in giuso l’ale;
10 quand’ io, che meco avea di quel d’Adamo, 11 vinto dal sonno, in su l’erba inchinai 12 là ’ve già tutti e cinque sedavamo.

query.result:
1 The concubine of ancient Tithonus 2 was already turning white on the eastern balcony, 3 out of the arms of her sweet lover;
4 her forehead was shining with gems, 5 set in the shape of the cold animal 6 that strikes people with its tail;
7 and the night, with the steps with which it ascends, 8 had taken two in the place where we were, 9 and the third was already lowering its wings;
10 when I, who had with me some of Adam's nature, 11 overcome by sleep, bowed down on the grass 12 where all five of us had been sitting.

31 There it seemed that she and I were burning;
32 and the imagined fire burned so fiercely,
33 that my sleep had to break.

34 In no other way did Achilles start up, 35 turning his awakened eyes around 36 and not knowing where he was,
37 when his mother spirited him away from Chiron to Scyros, 38 while he was sleeping in her arms, 39 from where the Greeks later took him away;
40 than I shook myself, as sleep fled from my face, 41 and I turned pale, 42 like a man who freezes, terrified.

